  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Again Responding to the Previous Rhyme, Presented to Damam
  author: Seong Sa-dal
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Upon the bedrock, in the pool's green embrace, clear waters gather.
    They plunge with fury, like a cart tumbling down a slope—
    surging and spilling, racing rapids startling in their flight.
    The aspect grows fearsome, wavering and dim, hardly the realm of men.
    In spiraling curves, the abyss darkens a thousand fathoms deep;
    what use to drop a pole or string together roots?
    Where does the great spirit find purchase and support?
    White silk billows forth, pearls pounding in the mortar, shaking the cliffs.

    At first I heard the rain suspended in the distant sky,
    then suddenly saw a white dragon crossing half the heavens.
    Thunder crashes and crackles; soft sounds flow like bamboo pipes singing.
    Why seek out Incense Burner Peak? What does it matter?
    The folk say Park Lang died, becoming the Falls of Park Yeon,
    where water winds and water-spirits forever drift the mist.

    In awe I stand upon the rocky shore,
    gazing at ten thousand wonders beyond all reckoning.
    I marvel at the clever craft of the Maker of Things.
    Say not this water turns its back upon the realm—
    it winds and circles, entering at last the Yeseong River.
    The ancient sages established law with purpose:
    the Four Kings' suppression derives from ages past.
    In the flow and ebb of things, each has its season;
    how can I fix the water's course or predict its way?
  footnotes:
    - 'Park Lang (박랑): A legendary figure associated with waterfalls in Korean folklore. According to local tradition, he perished and became identified with the falls, hence the name ''Falls of Park Yeon'' (박연폭포).'
    - 'The Yeseong River (예성강): A major river on the Korean peninsula that flows through what is now North and South Korea, historically significant as a boundary.'
    - 'The Four Kings (사정): Likely refers to celestial or earth deities in East Asian cosmology responsible for maintaining cosmic order.'
    - This poem employs the classical poetic device of rhyming with a previously composed work, a common practice among Korean literati of the Joseon period.
